  "text": "Western blot analysis. An aliquot of the homogenized sample that was used to determine the levels of COX-1 and COX-2 protein was also examined using standard immunoblotting methods [CITATION_1] . Human muscle samples were homogenized as described above. Total protein content was determined using a bicinchoninic acid protein assay kit (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA) and measured on a spectrophotometer (Tecan Safire 2, Durham, NC). Samples were diluted in Tris-glycine SDS sample buffer (Invitrogen, Grand Island, NY) and boiled for 5 min. Two-color fluorescent standard (LI-COR Biosciences, Lincoln, NE) and diluted samples (30 g) were loaded into each well of a 7.5% gel. Proteins were separated via SDS-PAGE in running buffer (Invitrogen) at 125 V for 15 min followed by 145 V for ϳ50 -55 min, allowing the dye front to reach the bottom of the gel for protein separation. A Mini PROTEAN Tetra electrophoresis system (Bio-Rad Laboratories, Hercules, CA) was used for protein separation. Proteins were transferred to nitrocellulose membranes, and membranes were blocked by incubation at room temperature for 1 h in PBS containing 1% Tween PBS (TPBS) and 3% dry milk (Kroger Brand, Cincinnati, OH). After blocking, membranes were incubated in a monoclonal anti-COX-1 (1:500 dilution, cat. no. 160110; Cayman Chemical) or polyclonal anti-COX-2 (1:500 dilution, cat. no. 160126; Cayman Chemical) TPBS solution overnight at 4°C. After TPBS washes (5 ϫ 5 min), the membranes were incubated in a fluorescent goat anti-rabbit IR 800 secondary antibody for detection of COX-2 and a fluorescent goat anti-mouse IR 800 secondary antibody for COX-1 detection. Membranes were once again washed in TPBS (5 ϫ 5 min), and bands were visualized using an Odyssey infrared imager (LI-COR). For all COX-1 membranes, the blots were lightly stripped using NaOH (0.2 M) for 2 min and then washed with TPBS and reblocked for 15 min. Blots were then rinsed and exposed to a TPBS/anti-GAPDH (1:15,000 dilution, cat. no. MAB374; Millipore, Temecula CA) incubation solution, incubated overnight at 4°C. The next day, membranes were washed, exposed to a fluorescent donkey anti-mouse IR680 secondary antibody, and imaged. GAPDH was used for verification of equal loading of protein. COX-2 membranes were not stripped between anti-COX-2 and GAPDH incubations. COX-2 antibody specificity was verified with LPS-stimulated RAW 264.7 mouse macrophage cell lysate (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Santa Cruz, CA) in a previous study [CITATION_2] . COX-1 antibody specificity was verified using human coronary vascular smooth muscle lysate [ Fig.  3B ; cells were purchased from ScienCell (Carlsbad, CA)]. All data were analyzed using Image Studio 2.0 software (LI-COR). Reagents for Western blot analysis were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich Chemical (St. Louis, MO) unless otherwise noted.",
